fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Given two cyclic trees (T \subseteq  X^*, \delta ) and (T' \subseteq  Y^*, \delta '), a map f : X^* \to  Y^* is a cyclic tree homomorphism when it satisfies:

       \begin {align*}            &f(\epsilon ) = \epsilon \\     &f(xt) = f(x)f(t)\\     &t \in  T \implies  f(t) \in  T'\\     &(t , t') \in  \delta  \implies  (f(t) , f(t')) \in  \delta '        \end {align*}   

  This essentially says that f is a free monoid homomorphism which additionally preserves the cyclic tree and cycle map.

